---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import Divider from '../components/Divider.astro';
import { TEACHINGS } from '../site.ts';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Maharaj-ji"
  description="The life, teachings and Hanuman-bhakti of Neem Karoli Baba — the saint of the Kumaon hills and founder of Kainchi Dham."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="The saint of the Kumaon hills"
    deva="नीम करोली बाबा"
    title="Maharaj-ji"
    lede="A great devotee of Hanuman who asked for nothing and gave everything — wrapped in a plaid blanket, feeding all who came."
  />

  <article class="shell-narrow prose-deva mj-body reveal">
    <p class="mj-lead">
      Neem Karoli Baba — known simply as <em>Maharaj-ji</em> to those who loved him — was one of
      the most beloved saints of modern India. He left no organisation, wrote no books, and
      sought no followers. And yet his love quietly reshaped countless lives, in India and far
      beyond, in ways still unfolding today.
    </p>

    <figure class="mj-figure" data-zoom>
      <img src="/images/baba/reading.jpg" alt="Neem Karoli Baba wrapped in his plaid blanket, reading" width="640" height="800" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>Maharaj-ji, wrapped in the blanket by which devotees still know him. <span class="mj-credit">Courtesy Durgamayi Ma Ashram</span></figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>A wandering sadhu</h2>
    <p>
      Born around the turn of the 20th century in a Brahmin family in Uttar Pradesh, he was
      married young, as was the custom — but the pull of God was stronger. He left home to live
      as a wandering <em>sadhu</em>, travelling across India under many names, sometimes
      recognised as a saint, often simply passing through.
    </p>
    <p>
      The name by which the world now knows him came from a small village. Riding a train
      without a ticket, he was asked to get down at a station called <strong>Neeb Karori</strong>.
      He stepped off, sat by the tracks, and the train — so the devotees say — would not move
      again until the railway officials begged him back aboard. He took the village's name as
      his own.
    </p>

    <Divider class="mj-rule" />

    <h2>Kainchi Dham</h2>
    <p>
      In the serene Kumaon hills near Nainital, where two streams meet between two hills shaped
      like the blades of a pair of scissors (<em>kainchi</em>), Maharaj-ji helped establish the
      ashram and Hanuman temple now known as <strong>Kainchi Dham</strong>. Its foundation is
      remembered each year on <strong>15 June</strong> with a great <em>bhandara</em> — a feast
      where thousands are fed, just as Maharaj-ji always insisted everyone should be.
    </p>

    <h2>Devotion to Hanuman</h2>
    <p>
      The whole of Maharaj-ji's life flowed from his love of <strong>Hanuman</strong> — the
      perfect devotee, strong and humble, whose only wish is to serve Ram. Maharaj-ji built
      Hanuman temples across India and would not let people touch his own feet; <em>touch
      Hanuman's feet instead</em>, he would say. To be near him was to be quietly turned back
      toward God.
    </p>

    <figure class="mj-figure mj-figure-wide" data-zoom>
      <img src="/images/baba/prasad.jpg" alt="Maharaj-ji being offered fruit; feeding everyone was his first instruction" width="900" height="600" loading="lazy" style="object-position:46% 24%" />
      <figcaption>“Feed everyone.” Prasad was, for Maharaj-ji, a form of love. <span class="mj-credit">Courtesy Durgamayi Ma Ashram</span></figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>His teaching, in four breaths</h2>
    <p>He gave no complicated philosophy. When people asked how to live, how to find God, he answered with a few plain instructions — and lived every one of them himself:</p>

    <ul class="mj-teachings">
      {TEACHINGS.map((t) => (
        <li><span class="mj-t-en">{t.en}</span><span class="mj-t-hi deva">{t.hi}</span></li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <blockquote>
      “Don't put anyone out of your heart.”
    </blockquote>

    <Divider class="mj-rule" />

    <h2>A few of his leelas</h2>
    <p>
      Devotees tell countless <em>leelas</em> — moments of divine play, small graces of knowing
      and love. A few are told again and again:
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>He knew everything.</strong> When Ram Dass first came, Maharaj-ji told him —
      quietly, unprompted — how and when his mother had died, details no one present could have
      known. Ram Dass wept. He had found his guru.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>The medicine that did nothing.</strong> Ram Dass once offered Maharaj-ji a large
      dose of LSD, certain it would show <em>something</em>. Baba swallowed it and waited, and
      nothing happened at all. He only smiled. What the chemical reached for, he simply already was.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Feed everyone.</strong> No one left him hungry. He would insist, again and again,
      that every visitor be fed — and the prasad, devotees say, always somehow stretched to meet
      the crowd.
    </p>

    <Divider class="mj-rule" />

    <h2>Mahasamadhi — and a love that travelled</h2>
    <p>
      Maharaj-ji left his body on <strong>11 September 1973</strong> in Vrindavan. But his
      presence had already crossed oceans. Western seekers who found him in the 1960s and 70s —
      among them <a href="/people/ram-dass/">Ram Dass</a>, <a href="/people/krishna-das/">Krishna
      Das</a>, and humanitarian <a href="/people/larry-brilliant/">Larry Brilliant</a> — carried
      his love home. Out of it came the book
      <em>Be Here Now</em>, a worldwide movement of kirtan, and the
      <a href="https://www.seva.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Seva Foundation</a>, which
      has restored sight to millions in his name.
    </p>
    <p>
      Today his dhams draw devotees from every corner of the earth. And in small rooms like
      ours in Nashik, on a Tuesday evening, the same lamp is lit and the same names are sung.
    </p>

    <p class="mj-jai deva">जय श्री राम · जय हनुमान</p>
  </article>

  <section class="shell mj-cta reveal">
    <div class="mj-cta-card card">
      <div>
        <h3>Sit with us on a Tuesday.</h3>
        <p>The simplest way to know Maharaj-ji is to come and sing.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/join/" class="btn btn-primary">Join the satsang</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .mj-body { padding: 1.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .mj-lead { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--color-ink); font-style: italic; }
  .mj-figure { margin: 2.4rem 0; cursor: zoom-in; }
  .mj-figure img {
    width: 100%; max-width: 30rem; display: block; margin-inline: auto;
    border-radius: 1rem;
    box-shadow: 0 30px 56px -32px color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-ink) 60%, transparent);
    transition: transform 0.4s var(--ease-soft);
  }
  .mj-figure:hover img { transform: translateY(-3px); }
  .mj-figure figcaption { text-align: center; font-size: 0.85rem; font-style: italic; color: var(--color-ink-faint); margin-top: 0.8rem; }
  .mj-figure-wide img { max-width: 40rem; }
  .mj-credit { display: block; font-style: normal; font-size: 0.72rem; letter-spacing: 0.06em; margin-top: 0.2rem; }
  .mj-rule { margin-block: 2.6rem; }
  .mj-teachings { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 1.4rem 0; display: grid; gap: 0.5rem; }
  .mj-teachings li { display: flex; align-items: baseline; justify-content: space-between; gap: 1rem; padding: 0.7rem 1.1rem; background: var(--color-paper-warm); border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-gold) 25%, transparent); border-radius: 0.7rem; }
  .mj-teachings li::before { display: none; }
  .mj-t-en { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--color-ink); }
  .mj-t-hi { color: var(--color-maroon); }
  .mj-jai { text-align: center; font-size: 1.7rem; color: var(--color-maroon); margin-top: 2.6rem; }

  .mj-cta { padding: 2rem 0 1rem; }
  .mj-cta-card { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; gap: 1.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; padding: 2rem; }
  .mj-cta-card h3 { font-size: 1.5rem; }
  .mj-cta-card p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); margin-top: 0.3rem; }
</style>
